<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-635-393  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 635 393.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Dec 1990 v15 n13 p321(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Relational databases: the real story.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Vaughan-Nichols, Steven J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many people, including some database professionals, mistakenlybelieve that a relational database management system (RDBMS) isany program capable of accessing multiple databasessimultaneously.andP;  The true RDBMS model, as defined by Edgar Codd in1970, uses two-dimensional arrays of rows and columns to hold allinformation and is theoretically simpler to code than thetraditional hierarchical model, which stores data in a treestructure.andP;  Building an RDBMS is more difficult in practice thanin theory because all information must be manageable by relationalmeans.andP;  There is no agreement on how to manipulate recordscontaining null values or how to achieve distributionalindependence, which lets the data manager cope with distributeddata bases.andP;  Many data bases are hybrid systems that combinehierarchical and relational elements.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Relational DBMSRelational data basesData base management systemsSoftware DesignData Base Design.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>